    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-4246000">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-4246000">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,4246000)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-4246000">
																		A Less-than-brief Response
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/lt-flops" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1735419); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1735419&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204686" alt="Lt Flops" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1735419)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/lt-flops" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1735419); return false;" >Lt Flops</a></span> <span class="odate time_1557631881 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">12 May 2019 03:31</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4246000">
									

<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>That may be all well and good, but even classes like Thaumiel once held the title of &quot;esoteric&quot;. Thaumiel received its own tag after appearing in only <strong>two</strong> articles.<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-758529-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-758529-1')">1</a></sup> Different standards for a smaller site with a different tagging administration, to be sure, but this is no insignificant fact.</p>
<p>With a change in standards, it's harder to create and write for a non-standard class. But that difficulty shouldn't disincentivize writers &#8212; Thaumiel was once in the exact same position, and now look at the way we accept it as a narrative conceit. Object Classes are just as plastic as every other aspect of article format. Writers<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-758529-2" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-758529-2')">2</a></sup> like Scantron/CWW have proven just how easily things may bend, given a good enough reason.</p>
<p>There are classes that prevail above others; in the same way, there are esoteric classes that will pass the threshold of &quot;canon&quot; and become standard, like Thaumiel before them. For instance, look at Archon. In the span of one year, writers have written <strong>nine</strong> separate articles about it.</p>
<p>You <em>could</em> make the case that <em>most</em> esoteric classes are &quot;pointless gimmicks&quot;, and I won't deny you that, but some have a decent chance at becoming the next big thing. The higher standards required to make them &quot;a thing&quot; will never dissuade writers from coming up with novel ideas. In fact, since it takes more work to solidify these concepts nowadays, they only feel even more legitimate. And so I would argue that your pushback against esoteric classes is only the driving force to make them stronger and more robust.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>TL;DR:</strong> We shouldn't disparage the esoteric classes just because they aren't well-known or don't seem &quot;useful&quot; enough. We should instead accept that creators will work very hard to produce interesting content, for which there is always a spot on this website. Thaumiel &#8212; an object class you yourself have used, even though it was once a pointless gimmick with no articles to its name &#8212; is a strong example.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
