		<div class="post" id="post-4246032">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,4246032)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-4246032">
																		Re: A Less-than-brief Response
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/a-random-day" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1841781); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1841781&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204686" alt="A Random Day" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1841781)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/a-random-day" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1841781); return false;" >A Random Day</a></span> <span class="odate time_1557635856 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">12 May 2019 04:37</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4246032">
									

<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Rebuttal</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Hide&nbsp;rebuttal</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>My response to that continues to be that niche object classes aren't interesting content. They're pointless gimmicks that require extra exposition to explain why the object doesn't fit into the S/E/K/T/E/N format, made all the worse by the fact that every object given a 'standard esoteric class' (which is oxymoronic all by itself) could just as easily be given a S/E/K/T/E/N class. Their contribution to site lore is negligible and the avenues they open up for new storytelling possibilities are limited to being able to put them as an object class.</p>
<p>Thaumiel worked because it occupied and defined a unique niche and space in both the object class and Foundation ideology to warrant its existence. Thaumiel is completely unlike Safe, Euclid, and Keter by virtue of the fact that it is not merely contained but actively exploited and relied upon by the Foundation. Moreover, its existence codified the idea that the Foundation was actively utilizing anomalies and even openly acknowledging the hypocrisy of using anomalies to contain anomalies in the name of pragmatism. It worked because it expanded the site lore in a meaningful way.</p>
<p>Archon can be defined in one of two ways: either it's contained by not containing it, in which case it's Safe; or it cannot effectively be contained without causing even more trouble, in which case it's Keter because the Foundation's whole job is to contain things. Th only lore Archon creates is its own pointless existence.</p>
<p>Hiemal is even worse; its author is quick to point out that Roget's Proposal, the original Thaumiel, should in fact be Hiemal &#8212; even though the mere statement that the original Thaumiel would work as a Hiemal only confirms Hiemal's sheer pointlessness in the face of Thaumiel's existence.</p>
<p>Apollyon worked thrice &#8212; once for shock factor and twice for poignancy &#8212; before its own saturation into the site lore ruined its original purpose and caused its creator to abandon it.</p>
<p>Maksur, Ticonderoga, Eparch, Godel, and all the rest are pointless gimmicks that do nothing but hook the reader by virtue of being unconventional, when that unconventionality is completely contrary to the point of having object classes.</p>
<p><strong>TL;DR</strong> Niche object classes aren't interesting content. They're pointless gimmicks that don't make sense in-universe and thus require extra exposition to explain why the object doesn't fit into the S/E/K/T/E/N format. This is made all the worse because every object given a 'standard esoteric class' (which is oxymoronic all by itself) could just as easily be given a S/E/K/T/E/N class. Thaumiel was never a pointless gimmick because unlike every other niche object class, it did not fit into the then-standard SEKEN mold and completely changed the Foundation's relationship with anomalies, both pragmatically and ideologically, thus opening up entirely new avenues of storytelling in the format.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

