					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/decibelles" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2005044); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2005044&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204686" alt="Decibelles" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2005044)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/decibelles" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2005044); return false;" >Decibelles</a></span> <span class="odate time_1557680165 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">12 May 2019 16:56</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4246642">
									

<p>I don't think a number of these entries should be on here. Just because an esoteric class is unique in usage doesn't make it feel like it <em>has</em> to be listed, unless it's one that needs explanation. For example, Keter/Friend is literally just Keter; why list that? Shaggy's Proposal is on that list twice due to its article fuckery, when its Apollyon usage can probably preclude it from being listed repeatedly. I'd rather see actual unique esoteric classes that could pass as being reusable rather than going by the ethos of literally listing every individual one. For example, Infohazardous Predator and Yesod, not At home and ??. Removing those, as well as removing redundant entries listed, would make the page feel tighter and more useful to someone who needs this.</p>
<p>I'll also criticize the inclusion of Joke Esoteric Classes here; a number of them feel disparate when taken outside of the context of their joke, and just feels like taking up page space, and even the ones that are &quot;arguably&quot; viable for standard documentation aren't because they're only used in a joke. Joke SCPs are the prime example of messing with object classes to achieve humor; listing them here feels humorless and seems to serve less purpose than the rest of the article does. The section could be excised with hardly anything missing.</p>
<p>Otherwise, the page looks good and is formatted nicely, and serves as a good resource for anyone who'd need this.</p>

							</div>

								
